04841nam a22006855i 9780814728604DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t19941994nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780814728604  a(DE-B1597)547576  a(OCoLC)782878115  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aLC1757b.F37 1994 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a376/.9752201 aFarnham, Christie Anne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Education of the Southern Belle :bHigher Education and Student Socialization in the Antebellum South /cChristie Anne Farnham. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1994] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE. Academic Life -- tCHAPTER 1. What's in a Name? Antebellum Female Colleges -- tCHAPTER 2. From Embroidery to Greek: Raising Academic Levels -- tCHAPTER 3. Educating a Lady: The Formal Curriculum -- tPART TWO. The World of the Female School -- tCHAPTER 4. The Yankee Dispersion: Faculty Life in Female Schools -- tCHAPTER 5. Trying to Look Very Fascinating: The Informal Curriculum -- tCHAPTER 6. Sisters: The Development of Sororities -- tCHAPTER 7. Lovers: Romantic Friendships -- tCHAPTER 8. Queens: May Day Queens as Symbol and Substance -- tEpilogue: The Enduring Image of the Southern Belle -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tName Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe American South before the Civil War was the site of an unprecedented social experiment in women's education. The South offered women an education explicitly designed to be equivalent to that of men, while maintaining and nurturing the gender conventions epitomized by the ideal of the Southern belle. This groundbreaking work provides us with an intimate picture of the entire social experience of antebellum women's colleges and seminaries in the South, analyzing the impact of these colleges upon the cultural construction of femininity among white Southern women, and their legacy for higher education. Christie Farnham investigates the contradiction involved in using a male-defined curricula to educate females, and explores how educators denied these incongruities. She also examines the impact of slavery on faculty and students. The emotional life of students is revealed through correspondence, journals, and scrapbooks, highlighting the role of sororities and romantic friendships among female pupils. Farnham ends with an analysis of how the end of the Civil War resulted in a failure to keep up with the advances that had been achieved in women's education. The most comprehensive history of this brief and unique period of reform to date, The Education of the Southern Belle is must reading for anyone interested in women's studies, Southern history, the history of American education, and female friendship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEducation, HigherxCurriculazSouthern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectszSouthern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aInterpersonal relationsxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenxEducation (Higher)zSouthern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenxSocializationzSouthern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081472615040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814728604423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814728604/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBA